What a builder actually learns (non-mystical, very real)

1. Reality has structure
	•	Wood has grain, limits, strengths
	•	You don’t “decide” what works—you discover it
→ This trains respect for invariants (what doesn’t change)

⸻

2. Relationships matter more than parts
	•	A beam alone means nothing
	•	The joint determines whether the structure holds
→ This builds intuition for systems, not isolated pieces

⸻

3. Invisible forces are real
	•	Load, tension, compression—you can’t see them, but you must account for them
→ You learn to reason about hidden variables

⸻

4. Small errors compound
	•	A slight misalignment early = big failure later
→ Sensitivity to initial conditions and drift

⸻

5. Build → test → adjust
	•	You don’t theorize forever—you construct and see what holds
→ Feedback-driven understanding

⸻

How that maps to how someone might see the world

Not as “secret knowledge,” but as a trained perception style:
	•	Look for underlying structure, not surface appearance
	•	Think in relationships and consequences
	•	Respect constraints instead of ignoring them
	•	Value foundations over decoration
	•	Use simple models that hold under stress

